                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>The memorandum attached to Mr. Miller’s memorandum to the Secretary of October
                    30, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>, was later recast by the <gloss
                        target="#t_IBRD1">IBRD</gloss> into the form of a proposal of the <gloss
                        target="#t_IBRD1">IBRD</gloss> to the <gloss target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss>
                    rather than an agreement between the <gloss target="#t_IBRD1">IBRD</gloss> and
                    the State Department. The State and Treasury Departments jointly suggested this
                    revision, in which the substance of the <gloss target="#t_IBRD1">IBRD</gloss>
                    proposals regarding loan policy towards Brazil remained unchanged.</p>
                <p>On November 17 the Export-Import Bank, to which the revised proposal had been
                    passed for informal review, stated that the <gloss target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss>,
                    in confining Brazilian loans of the Export-Import Bank to two strictly limited
                    categories, would renounce rights and responsibilities conferred upon United
                    States agencies by law and restrict the foreign financial and diplomatic powers
                    of the United States. The Bank further expressed the hope that the proposal
                    would not formally be submitted to the <gloss target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss>.</p>
                <pb facs="0797" n="781" xml:id="pg_781"/>
                <p>Documentation is contained in file 398.14 for November 1950 and in <gloss
                        target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss> Document No. 1078, December 12, 1950, Lot 60 D
                    137.</p>
            </div>
